events.description: A sunspot is observed by Han dynasty astronomers during the reign of Emperor Cheng of Han, one of the earliest dated sunspot observations in China.
events.html: • 28 BC – A sunspot is observed by Han dynasty astronomers during the reign of Emperor Cheng of Han, one of the earliest dated sunspot observations in China.[1]

entities.name: Science and technology of the Han dynasty

events.description: Scottish nobles recognize the authority of Edward I of England pending the selection of a king.
events.html: • 1291 – Scottish nobles recognize the authority of Edward I of England pending the selection of a king.[2]

events.description: Temür, Khagan of the Mongols, is enthroned as Emperor of the Yuan dynasty.
events.html: • 1294 – Temür, Khagan of the Mongols, is enthroned as Emperor of the Yuan dynasty.[3]

events.description: Amerigo Vespucci allegedly leaves Cádiz for his first voyage to the New World.
events.html: • 1497 – Amerigo Vespucci allegedly leaves Cádiz for his first voyage to the New World.[4]

events.description: Christopher Columbus visits the Cayman Islands and names them Las Tortugas after the numerous turtles there.
events.html: • 1503 – Christopher Columbus visits the Cayman Islands and names them Las Tortugas after the numerous turtles there.[5]

events.description: Jacques Cartier visits Newfoundland.
events.html: • 1534 – Jacques Cartier visits Newfoundland.[6]

events.description: King Narai nominates Phetracha as regent, leading to the revolution of 1688 in which Phetracha becomes king of the Ayutthaya Kingdom.
events.html: • 1688 – King Narai nominates Phetracha as regent, leading to the revolution of 1688 in which Phetracha becomes king of the Ayutthaya Kingdom.[7]

events.description: Great Northern War: The Russian Navy led by Admiral Fyodor Apraksin land both at Katajanokka and Hietalahti during the Battle of Helsinki.
events.html: • 1713 – Great Northern War: The Russian Navy led by Admiral Fyodor Apraksin land both at Katajanokka and Hietalahti during the Battle of Helsinki.[8]

events.description: Rioting occurs in London after John Wilkes is imprisoned for writing an article for The North Briton severely criticizing King George III.
events.html: • 1768 – Rioting occurs in London after John Wilkes is imprisoned for writing an article for The North Briton severely criticizing King George III.[9]

entities.name: George III of the United Kingdom

events.description: The Parliament of Great Britain passes the Tea Act, designed to save the British East India Company by reducing taxes on its tea and granting it the right to sell tea directly to North America. The legislation leads to the Boston Tea Party.
events.html: • 1773 – The Parliament of Great Britain passes the Tea Act, designed to save the British East India Company by reducing taxes on its tea and granting it the right to sell tea directly to North America. The legislation leads to the Boston Tea Party.[10]

events.description: Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette become King and Queen of France.
events.html: • 1774 – Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette become King and Queen of France.[11]

events.description: American Revolutionary War: A small Colonial militia led by Ethan Allen and Colonel Benedict Arnold captures Fort Ticonderoga.
events.html: • 1775 – American Revolutionary War: A small Colonial militia led by Ethan Allen and Colonel Benedict Arnold captures Fort Ticonderoga.[12]

events.description: American Revolutionary War: The Second Continental Congress takes place in Philadelphia.
events.html: • 1775 – American Revolutionary War: The Second Continental Congress takes place in Philadelphia.[13]

events.description: War of the First Coalition: Napoleon wins a victory against Austrian forces at Lodi bridge over the Adda River in Italy. The Austrians lose some 2,000 men.
events.html: • 1796 – War of the First Coalition: Napoleon wins a victory against Austrian forces at Lodi bridge over the Adda River in Italy. The Austrians lose some 2,000 men.[14]

events.description: First Barbary War: The Barbary pirates of Tripoli declare war on the United States of America.
events.html: • 1801 – First Barbary War: The Barbary pirates of Tripoli declare war on the United States of America.[15]

events.description: The National Gallery in London opens to the public.
events.html: • 1824 – The National Gallery in London opens to the public.[16]

events.description: A revolt broke out in southern Vietnam against Emperor Minh Mang, who had desecrated the deceased mandarin Le Van Duyet.
events.html: • 1833 – A revolt broke out in southern Vietnam against Emperor Minh Mang, who had desecrated the deceased mandarin Le Van Duyet.[17]

events.description: Panic of 1837: New York City banks suspend the payment of specie, triggering a national banking crisis and an economic depression whose severity was not surpassed until the Great Depression.
events.html: • 1837 – Panic of 1837: New York City banks suspend the payment of specie, triggering a national banking crisis and an economic depression whose severity was not surpassed until the Great Depression.[18]

entities.name: Great Depression in the United States

events.description: Astor Place Riot: A riot breaks out at the Astor Opera House in Manhattan, New York City over a dispute between actors Edwin Forrest and William Charles Macready, killing at least 22 and injuring over 120.
events.html: • 1849 – Astor Place Riot: A riot breaks out at the Astor Opera House in Manhattan, New York City over a dispute between actors Edwin Forrest and William Charles Macready, killing at least 22 and injuring over 120.[19]

events.description: Indian Rebellion of 1857: In India, the first war of Independence begins. Sepoys mutiny against their commanding officers at Meerut.
events.html: • 1857 – Indian Rebellion of 1857: In India, the first war of Independence begins. Sepoys mutiny against their commanding officers at Meerut.[20]

events.description: American Civil War: In Kentucky, Union soldiers ambush and mortally wound Confederate raider William Quantrill, who lingers until his death on June 6.
events.html: • 1865 – American Civil War: In Kentucky, Union soldiers ambush and mortally wound Confederate raider William Quantrill, who lingers until his death on June 6.[21]

events.description: The First transcontinental railroad, linking the eastern and western United States, is completed at Promontory Summit, Utah Territory with the golden spike.
events.html: • 1869 – The First transcontinental railroad, linking the eastern and western United States, is completed at Promontory Summit, Utah Territory with the golden spike.[22]

events.description: Victoria Woodhull becomes the first woman nominated for President of the United States.
events.html: • 1872 – Victoria Woodhull becomes the first woman nominated for President of the United States.[23]

events.description: The Centennial Exposition is opened in Philadelphia.
events.html: • 1876 – The Centennial Exposition is opened in Philadelphia.[24]

events.description: Carol I is crowned the King of the Romanian Kingdom.
events.html: • 1881 – Carol I is crowned the King of the Romanian Kingdom.[25]

events.description: Finnish farmworker Karl Emil Malmelin kills seven people with an axe at the Simola croft in the village of Klaukkala.
events.html: • 1899 – Finnish farmworker Karl Emil Malmelin kills seven people with an axe at the Simola croft in the village of Klaukkala.[26][27]

events.description: The Horch & Cir. Motorwagenwerke AG is founded. It would eventually become the Audi company.
events.html: • 1904 – The Horch & Cir. Motorwagenwerke AG is founded. It would eventually become the Audi company.[28]

events.description: Mother's Day is observed for the first time in the United States, in Grafton, West Virginia.
events.html: • 1908 – Mother's Day is observed for the first time in the United States, in Grafton, West Virginia.[29]

events.description: Sailing in the lifeboat James Caird, Ernest Shackleton arrives at South Georgia after a journey of 800 nautical miles from Elephant Island.
events.html: • 1916 – Sailing in the lifeboat James Caird, Ernest Shackleton arrives at South Georgia after a journey of 800 nautical miles from Elephant Island.[30]

entities.name: South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands

events.description: The United States annexes the Kingman Reef.
events.html: • 1922 – The United States annexes the Kingman Reef.[31]

events.description: J. Edgar Hoover is appointed first Director of the United States' Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), and remains so until his death in 1972.
events.html: • 1924 – J. Edgar Hoover is appointed first Director of the United States' Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), and remains so until his death in 1972.[32]

events.description: Censorship: In Germany, the Nazis stage massive public book burnings.
events.html: • 1933 – Censorship: In Germany, the Nazis stage massive public book burnings.[33]

events.description: World War II: German fighters accidentally bomb the German city of Freiburg.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: German fighters accidentally bomb the German city of Freiburg.[34]

events.description: World War II: Winston Churchill is appointed Prime Minister of the United Kingdom following the resignation of Neville Chamberlain. On the same day, Germany invades France, The Netherlands, Belgium and Luxembourg. Meanwhile, the United Kingdom occupies Iceland.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: Winston Churchill is appointed Prime Minister of the United Kingdom following the resignation of Neville Chamberlain. On the same day, Germany invades France, The Netherlands, Belgium and Luxembourg.[35] Meanwhile, the United Kingdom occupies Iceland.[36]

entities.name: Prime Minister of the United Kingdom

events.description: World War II: The House of Commons in London is damaged by the Luftwaffe in an air raid.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: The House of Commons in London is damaged by the Luftwaffe in an air raid.[37]

events.description: World War II: Rudolf Hess parachutes into Scotland to try to negotiate a peace deal between the United Kingdom and Nazi Germany.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: Rudolf Hess parachutes into Scotland to try to negotiate a peace deal between the United Kingdom and Nazi Germany.[38]

events.description: World War II: The Thai Phayap Army invades the Shan States during the Burma Campaign.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: The Thai Phayap Army invades the Shan States during the Burma Campaign.[39]

events.description: First successful launch of an American V-2 rocket at White Sands Proving Ground.
events.html: • 1946 – First successful launch of an American V-2 rocket at White Sands Proving Ground.[40]

events.description: Air France Flight 406 is destroyed by a bomb over the Sahara, killing 78.
events.html: • 1961 – Air France Flight 406 is destroyed by a bomb over the Sahara, killing 78.[41]

events.html: • 1962 – Marvel Comics publishes the first issue of The Incredible Hulk.[42]

events.html: • 1967 – The Northrop M2-F2 crashes on landing, becoming the inspiration for the novel Cyborg and TV series The Six Million Dollar Man.[43]

events.description: Vietnam War: The Battle of Dong Ap Bia begins with an assault on Hill 937. It will ultimately become known as Hamburger Hill.
events.html: • 1969 – Vietnam War: The Battle of Dong Ap Bia begins with an assault on Hill 937. It will ultimately become known as Hamburger Hill.[44]

events.description: In Thailand, a fire at the Kader Toy Factory kills over 200 workers.
events.html: • 1993 – In Thailand, a fire at the Kader Toy Factory kills over 200 workers.[46]

events.html: • 1996 – A blizzard strikes Mount Everest, killing eight climbers by the next day.[48]

events.description: A hand grenade thrown by Vladimir Arutyunian lands about 20 m from U.S. President George W. Bush while he is giving a speech to a crowd in Tbilisi, Georgia, but it malfunctions and does not detonate.
events.html: • 2005 – A hand grenade thrown by Vladimir Arutyunian lands about 20 m from U.S. President George W. Bush while he is giving a speech to a crowd in Tbilisi, Georgia, but it malfunctions and does not detonate.[51]
